<p>I am unsuccessfully trying to make the label of some forms I generate through a loop depend on <code>forloop.counter</code>. Here what I have so far:</p>  <pre><code>{% for field in form %}  {% formfield field with label="blablabla {{ forloop.counter }}" %}  {% endfor %} </code></pre>  <p>This returns the correct form but {{ forloop.counter }} appears as is in the label, instead of it being replaced by its value. </p>  <p>What am I doing wrong? I see this kind of construction everywhere in Django code, e.g. on <a href="https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.4/intro/tutorial04/" rel="nofollow">https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.4/intro/tutorial04/</a></p>  <pre><code>&lt;h1&gt;{{ poll.question }}&lt;/h1&gt;  {% if error_message %}&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;{{ error_message }}&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;{% endif %}  &lt;form action="/polls/{{ poll.id }}/vote/" method="post"&gt; {% csrf_token %} {% for choice in poll.choice_set.all %}     &lt;input type="radio" name="choice" id="choice{{ forloop.counter }}" value="{{ choice.id }}" /&gt;     &lt;label for="choice{{ forloop.counter }}"&gt;{{ choice.choice }}&lt;/label&gt;&lt;br /&gt; {% endfor %} &lt;input type="submit" value="Vote" /&gt; &lt;/form&gt; </code></pre>  <p>What sets forms' labels apart from say <code>id</code> in the above example that makes it impossible to parse <code>{{ forloop.counter }}</code> into strings?</p>